{"title_page": "Soul Plane", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Soul Plane\n| image          = Soul Plane poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Jessy Terrero]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* David Scott Rubin\n* Jessy Terrero}}\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* Chuck Wilson\n* Bo Zenga}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|<!--PER POSTER BILLING BLOCK-->\n* [[Tom Arnold (actor)|Tom Arnold]]\n* [[Kevin Hart]]\n* [[Method Man]]\n* [[Snoop Dogg]]}}\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[RZA]]\n* [[Christopher Lennertz]] {{small|(Uncredited)}}}}\n| cinematography = [[Jonathan Sela]]\n| editing        = Michael R. Miller\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* Boz Productions\n* Turbo Productions\n* [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]}}\n| distributor    = [[MGM Distribution Co.]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2004|05|28}}\n| runtime        = 86 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 86:28--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/soul-plane-2004-2 | title=''SOUL PLANE'' (18) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=July 22, 2004 | accessdate=March 3, 2015}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $16 million<ref name=\"mojo\"/>\n| gross          = $14.8 million<ref name=\"mojo\"/>\n}}\n'''''Soul Plane''''' is a 2004 American [[comedy film]] directed by [[Jessy Terrero]], written by Bo Zenga and starring [[Tom Arnold (actor)|Tom Arnold]], [[Kevin Hart]], [[Method Man]] and [[Snoop Dogg]]. Supporting actors include [[Mo'Nique]], [[Loni Love]], [[K.D. Aubert]], [[D.L. Hughley]], [[Godfrey (comedian)|Godfrey]] and [[Sof\u00eda Vergara|Sofia Vergara]]. The film revolves around multiple characters in different scenarios on-board an airplane. ''Soul Plane'' garnered negative reviews from critics and was a [[box office bomb]], grossing $14 million worldwide against a $16 million budget.\n\n==Plot==\nNashawn Wade ([[Kevin Hart (actor)|Kevin Hart]]) claims that he has loved planes since he was a baby, but he has a horrible experience with a typical [[airline]]: his dog Dre was classified as a [[checked baggage]] instead of a [[Hand luggage|carry-on]], he eats a horrible [[airline meal]], his buttocks gets stuck in the toilet while he has [[diarrhea]] (due to his meal) during turbulence, and Dre is sucked and killed through a jet engine to his death (after a stewardess accidentally opens the cargo door). Nashawn is taken away after an emergency landing with an ice cube on his buttocks to cool it off from turbulence. In response to the torture he has, he sues the airline and is awarded $100,000,000 by the jury. He decides to use the money to start his own airline, called N.W.A. (Nashawn Wade Airlines), whose acronym and logo are a pop culture reference to rap group [[N.W.A]]. The airline specifically caters to African Americans and hip hop culture.  The [[Airport terminal|terminal]] at the airport is called the [[Malcolm X]] terminal, where two non-working [[Transportation Security Administration|TSA]] Agents, Jamiqua ([[Mo'Nique]]) and Shaniece ([[Loni Love]]), are goofing off instead of checking belongings. The plane is a heavily modified [[Boeing 747SP]], customized with low-rider [[hydraulics]], [[Spinner (wheel)|spinners]], [[Wingtip device|blended winglets]] to compensate for the drag from the decorations, and a dance club. The [[Pre-flight safety demonstration|safety video]] is also a parody of the [[Destiny's Child]] song \"[[Survivor (Destiny's Child song)|Survivor]]\".\n\nAfter taking off from [[Los Angeles International Airport]], Nashawn must deal with a multitude of problems, starting with his [[Acrophobia|acrophobic]] captain, Captain Mack ([[Snoop Dogg]]). At a cruising altitude of Flight Level 330, it is revealed that he has never left the ground because he learned to fly on computer simulators in prison. Meanwhile, his cousin Muggsey ([[Method Man]]) sets up a miniature casino and strip joint in one of the areas of the plane (as seen in the workprint and unrated versions of the film), and Nashawn's ex-girlfriend is on board and less than happy to see him. Meanwhile, the Hunkee family, the only caucasian passengers on board, must also deal with their own problems; Elvis Hunkee's ([[Tom Arnold (actor)|Tom Arnold]]) daughter is turning 18 and plans to use her newfound freedom by drinking and having sex, his son has transformed from an exact duplicate of him to a stereotypical [[wigger]], and his wife has found a new interest in black men after viewing pictures in a pornographic magazine.\n\nCaptain Mack seemingly dies after eating mushrooms that the co-pilot, First Officer Gaemon ([[Godfrey (comedian)|Godfrey]]), uses to soothe his [[Crab louse|genital crabs]]. Nashawn attempts to contact Gaemon, who is incapacitated after slipping near a hot tub, forcing Nashawn to attempt to land the plane himself. Nashawn lands the plane safely, using the airplane stewardess' ([[Sof\u00eda Vergara]]) flight knowledge which she learned while having sex in the cockpit with the pilot on another plane. The plane lands in the middle of [[Central Park]] instead of [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]], and the spinners are stolen from the plane. Nashawn reconciles with his ex-girlfriend after earlier revealing to her that he only broke up with her so she would not give up her college opportunities for him.\n\nThe movie ends with Nashawn telling the audience the fate of his crew. He claims that he and his ex-girlfriend are back together taking their relationship slow this time around, his cousin Muggsey has started a strip club and gambling casino located in another airplane similar to the club in Nashawn's plane, Elvis Hunkee has begun a sexual relationship with one of the abrasive airline security guards ([[Mo'Nique]]), and Elvis Hunkee's son has become a major music video director but has disappeared shortly after filming a [[Michael Jackson]] video. Captain Mack later wakes up with both his chain and clothing stolen.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Kevin Hart]] as Nashawn Wade\n* [[Snoop Dogg]] as Captain Antoine Mack\n* [[Tom Arnold (actor)|Tom Arnold]] as Elvis Hunkee\n* [[Method Man]] as Muggsy\n* [[K. D. Aubert]] as Giselle\n* [[Godfrey (comedian)|Godfrey]] as Leslie Gaemon\n* [[Brian Hooks]] as D.J.\n* [[Arielle Kebbel]] as Heather Hunkee\n* [[Loni Love]] as Shaniece\n* [[Mo'Nique]] as Jamiqua\n* [[Sof\u00eda Vergara]] as Blanca\n* [[Missi Pyle]] as Barbara Hunkee\n* [[Sommore]] as Cherry\n* [[D.L. Hughley]] as Johnny\n* [[Ryan Pinkston]] as Billy Hunkee\n* [[Gary Anthony Williams]] as Flame\n* [[John Witherspoon (actor)|John Witherspoon]] as Blind Man\n* [[Cynthia Pinot]] as Hardrock girl\n* [[Angell Conwell]] as Tamika\n* [[Roberto Roman]] as Passenger\n* [[Terry Crews]] as Bouncer\n* [[Richard T. Jones]] as False Denzel\n* [[Lil Jon]] as himself\n* [[Ying Yang Twins]] as themselves\n* [[Karl Malone]] as himself\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Release==\n===Box office===\n''Soul Plane'' opened on May 28, 2004 in 1,566 theaters. In its opening weekend, the film made $5,648,486 in the domestic box office, ranking number five behind ''[[Shrek 2]]'', ''[[The Day After Tomorrow]]'', ''[[Troy (2004 film)|Troy]]'', and ''[[Raising Helen]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2004&wknd=22&p=.htm|title=Weekend Box Office Results for May 28-30, 2004|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|date=May 29, 2004|accessdate=March 3, 2015}}</ref> At the end of its run, the film grossed $14,190,750 domestically and $631,596 overseas for a worldwide total of $14,822,346.<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=soulplane.htm|title=Soul Plane (2004)|website=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Internet Movie Database|date=August 6, 2004|accessdate=March 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview on the podcast ''[[WTF with Marc Maron]]'', Hart said that part of the reason for the poor box office turnout was due to bootlegging, which had apparently begun three months before the film was released in theaters. He explained, \"on the street, [''Soul Plane''] made 40 million dollars\". Hart told [[Marc Maron]] that during a premiere, fans were coming up to him asking him to sign copies of the bootleg. Hart does, however, credit ''Soul Plane'' for making him popular enough to start touring around the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wtfpod.libsyn.com/webpage/episode-272-kevin-hart|title=WTF with Marc Maron Podcast: Episode 272 - Kevin Hart|website=Wtfpod.libsyn.com|date=April 19, 2012|accessdate=June 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\nThe film received negative reviews from critics. Review aggregator website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gave it an 18% approval rating and a [[weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] from a total of 101 reviews, with a consensus calling it a \"raunchy sendup of ''[[Airplane!]]'' that never really takes off.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/soul_plane/|title=Soul Plane|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=September 22, 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a 33/100 rating based on 26 reviews, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/soul-plane|title=Soul Plane|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>\n\n[[Stephen Holden]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' says in his review: \"This hectic farce, which pushes every envelope, is so broad and relentlessly raunchy that it makes a spoof like ''Airplane'' seem as demure as a vintage drawing-room comedy.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=940DE3D9103EF93BA15756C0A9629C8B63|title=Movie Review - Soul Plane|last=Holden|first=Stephen|authorlink=Stephen Holden|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 28, 2004|accessdate=March 3, 2015}}</ref> ''[[The A.V. Club]]''{{'}}s [[Nathan Rabin]] criticized the film for having stereotypical characters and humor made up of \"desperate half-gags further botched by clumsy camera work and atrocious timing.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://film.avclub.com/soul-plane-1798199639|title=Soul Plane|last=Rabin|first=Nathan|authorlink=Nathan Rabin|newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|date=June 1, 2004|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> Despite giving credit to Hart, Hughley and Snoop for their performances, Marc Savlov of ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]'' felt that the rest of the film's sophomoric gags \"only serves to make the rest of the production that much more humorless in contrast.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/events/film/2004-05-28/212582/|title=Soul Plane - Movie Review|last=Savlov|first=Marc|newspaper=[[The Austin Chronicle]]|date=May 28, 2004|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2014, the film appeared on ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine's users-voted list of \"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\", ranking number 47. Its given reason for being listed states: \"This was billed as an \"urban\" take on ''Airplane!'' That's a bad idea to begin with: like ''Scary Movie'', parodies of a parody are on to a loser from the start. But with the addition of crude racial stereotyping (of all races) and a fatal lack of funny, this goes from bad to worst. If more voters had seen it, this would be in the top ten.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.empireonline.com/features/50-worst-movies-ever/default.asp?film=47|title=The 50 Worst Movies Ever - 47. Soul Plane|magazine=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|publisher=[[Bauer Verlagsgruppe|Bauer]]|date=December 11, 2014|accessdate=March 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Film|Comedy}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0367085|Soul Plane}}\n* {{mojo title|soulplane|Soul Plane}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|soul_plane|Soul Plane}}\n* {{metacritic film|soul-plane|Soul Plane}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT